item.title: London
item.dc:creator: Minimalio
item.content:encoded:
London

Focusing on overlooked corners and shadowed alleyways, this project reveals the quiet poetry of urban design. Unusual perspectives and tight framing challenge the viewer’s sense of scale. The series evokes a mood of solitude amid chaos. The photographer used natural light at dusk to highlight textures and soft contrasts. It’s a tribute to the city’s unnoticed beauty.

item.title: Berlin
item.dc:creator: Minimalio
item.content:encoded:
Berlin

Set in the high-rise business districts of Berlin, this series emphasizes brutal surfaces and towering concrete facades. Structures and long exposures bring a cinematic edge to the shots. The work explores the tension between modernity and overdevelopment. Skyscrapers loom like monoliths, blurring the line between architecture and art. The atmosphere is vibrant yet unsettling.

item.title: New York
item.dc:creator: Minimalio
item.content:encoded:
NEW YORK

This project captures the stark lines and geometric forms of NY’s Brutalist architecture. Each frame isolates repetitive concrete patterns, transforming them into abstract compositions. The photographer used overcast skies to eliminate shadows and focus attention on form. Subtle tonal contrasts enhance the feeling of cold detachment. The result is a visual study in symmetry and structure.

item.title: About me
item.dc:creator: Minimalio
item.content:encoded:
About me

My series explores abandoned and weathered buildings left from the city’s mid-century modernist era. I like crumbling facades and faded murals that suggest both grandeur and neglect. I like to photograph early morning mist to enhance the feeling of time standing still. Each image invites reflection on urban decay and cultural memory. It’s a visual elegy for forgotten space
